04650nam a22006495i 9780226595825DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265958257 a10.7208/97802265958252doi  a(DE-B1597)523237  a(OCoLC)1084315514  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aGE50b.T86 2019 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a304.209182/12231 aTurchetti, Simone, eauthor.10aGreening the Alliance :bThe Diplomacy of NATO's Science and Environmental Initiatives /cSimone Turchetti. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b19 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tArchives Consulted (and Abbreviations Used to Identify Them) -- tIntroduction: NATO's Imperatives -- t1. Setting the Atmosphere -- t2. The Surveillance Ambitions of NATO's Science Program -- t3. The Storms of Dr. Strangelove: Environmental Warfare and the Science Committee Crisis -- t4. Launching NATO's Environmental Program -- t5. NATO's "Greening" in the Decade of Inflation -- t6. Strange Bedfellows: Environmental Monitoring and Surveillance -- t7. Science, Stability, and Climate Change -- t8. Epilogue: An Evergreen Alliance? -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFollowing the launch of Sputnik, the North Atlantic Treaty Organization became a prominent sponsor of scientific research in its member countries, a role it retained until the end of the Cold War. As NATO marks sixty years since the establishment of its Science Committee, the main organizational force promoting its science programs, Greening the Alliance is the first book to chart NATO's scientific patronage-and the motivations behind it-from the organization's early days to the dawn of the twenty-first century. Drawing on previously unseen documents from NATO's own archives, Simone Turchetti reveals how its investments were rooted in the alliance's defense and surveillance needs, needs that led it to establish a program prioritizing environmental studies. A long-overlooked and effective diplomacy exercise, NATO's "greening" at one point constituted the organization's chief conduit for negotiating problematic relations between allies. But while Greening the Alliance explores this surprising coevolution of environmental monitoring and surveillance, tales of science advisers issuing instructions to bomb oil spills with napalm or Dr. Strangelove-like experts eager to divert the path of hurricanes with atomic weapons make it clear: the coexistence of these forces has not always been harmonious. Reflecting on this rich, complicated legacy in light of contemporary global challenges like climate change, Turchetti offers both an eye-opening history of international politics and environmental studies and a thoughtful assessment of NATO's future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aEnvironmental protectionxResearchxHistory. 0aEnvironmental sciencesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEnvironmental sciencesxPolitical aspects. 0aResearchxHistoryy20th century. 0aResearchxPolitical aspects. 4aAtlantic Alliance. 4aCold War. 4aInternational Relations. 4aatmospheric research. 4aenvironmental diplomacy. 4aenvironmental studies. 4ameteorology. 4aoceanography. 4aremote sensing. 4ascience diplomacy. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226595825423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226595825.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  